        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <date>5<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. Feb<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> 1876</date>
                    <salute>It is not the gift but the altar which sanctifieth the gift.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>And it is not the teapot but the fact that it is Charles Darwin’s teapot that gives it an immortal value in our eyes.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I will not quit the subject of your postscript until light is let in on every cranny of the question.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>With warm thanks &amp; strong affection, my dear Darwin yours | John Tyndall</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Tyndall alludes to Matthew 23:19. ‘Ye fools and blind: for whether is greater, the gift, or the altar that sanctifieth the gift?’</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had ordered a silver tea set as a wedding present (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10379.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Tyndall, 4 February 1876</ref> and nn. 1 and 2, and second letter from John Tyndall, 5 February 1876).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10379.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Tyndall, 4 February 1876</ref> and nn. 3 and 4. Tyndall had been working on the problem of spontaneous generation.</note>
        </div>        
            
